---
import Default from '../../layouts/Default.astro';
import Hero from '../../components/Hero.astro';
import SectionHead from '../../components/SectionHead.astro';
import PullQuote from '../../components/PullQuote.astro';
---
<Default title="HIVE Product Lab · Harshith Kantamneni" description="Autonomous Claude lab shipping iOS apps end-to-end. Director plus ~46 specialists. Twelve cycles of byte-identical builds and counting." current="labs">

  <Hero
    meta={['Active 2026', '~46 agents', 'iOS / Swift']}
  >
    HIVE.<br />Product Lab.
  </Hero>

  <div class="page-grid">
    <p class="extended measure-narrow lede" style="margin-top: var(--space-6);">
      HIVE ships iOS apps end-to-end. A Director on Opus runs the show; ~46 specialists
      do the work. Cycles run continuously. After each one, the Director writes down
      what to change about how the lab works. Never what to build next.
    </p>
  </div>

  <SectionHead marker="OPERATING" title="How it runs" />

  <div class="page-grid">
    <div class="extended measure-tight drop-cap">
      <p>Each cycle has one target. Right now, that target is a shippable iOS app. The Director allocates work, routes it, reviews it, and writes the post-cycle directive. It doesn't execute code itself.</p>
      <p>Specialists handle the actual work: architects design, implementers build, verifiers test, reviewers attack the merge candidate. About 46 of them at any given time. They argue, vote, and move on.</p>
      <p>Memory is three layers of markdown. Long-term holds the ratified rules. Cycle holds what's happening this run. Conversation holds what the agent is currently thinking, and gets wiped between turns. That last part is deliberate: it stops one specialist's working hypothesis from polluting the next decision.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <PullQuote attribution="Operating principle">
    The Director writes meta-rules, not tactics. Trust the loops; intervene only when loops fail.
  </PullQuote>

  <SectionHead marker="VERIFICATION" title="Why byte-identical builds matter" />

  <div class="page-grid">
    <div class="extended measure-tight">
      <p>Twelve consecutive cycles, same source in, same binary out, byte for byte. That sounds like nothing happened. It actually means something specific: no specialist agent introduced an undeclared change to the build output during those two weeks. Anything that should have shown up would have shown up as a hash mismatch.</p>
      <p>The point isn't the bytes. It's that drift in the build is now legible from outside the lab. Without that, every "build still passes" claim is just another self-reported number.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <SectionHead marker="SELF-CORRECTION" title="Meta-rules, not tactics" />

  <div class="page-grid">
    <div class="extended measure-tight">
      <p>The lab corrects itself through directives written between cycles. The rule for what counts as a directive is strict: meta-rules only. Process changes, constraint changes, gate changes. Never "do X this cycle."</p>
      <p>"Do X this cycle" is the wrong shape because it crowds out the lab's own judgment, which is the whole point of running it autonomously. "When condition Y holds, the verification gate must include external review before merge" is the right shape. It tightens structure without prescribing the move.</p>
      <p>The interesting failure mode is when the Director starts smuggling tactics into meta-rules. That's what the post-cycle review process is for: catch the smuggle before it ratifies.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

</Default>
